</head>

<body>

<h1>@HI{{wa}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> <strong>@HI{{wa}}</strong>. 
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{wa}}</strong> is a sentence ending particle mainly used by women. It is used to:
<ul>
<li> indicate emotion or feelings of admiration
<li> soften the tone of a statement
</ul>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{wa}}</strong> has the same pronunciation as the topic marker <a href="grammar-particle-wa.html">@HI{{ha}}</a>
but is written with a different hiragana character.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{now^night}}no@KT{{opera}}ha,@KJ{{book^hit}}nisubarashikatta<strong>wa</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Tonight's concert was absolutely fabulous.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{hokano@KJ{{store}}de@KJ{{buy}}ttano@KJ{{direction}}gaiito@KJ{{think}}u<strong>wa</strong>}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I think it would be better to buy it from another store.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{wa}}</strong> can follow any declarative sentence but cannot follow volitional forms of verbs and cannot follow questions.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{wa}}</strong> can occur with other sentence-ending particles, such as <a href="grammar-particle-ne.html">@HI{{ne}}</a>
and <a href="grammar-particle-yo.html">@HI{{yo}}</a>. In such cases <strong>@HI{{wa}}</strong> must precede these particles.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}hamo@KJ{{going}}ku<strong>wa</strong>yo.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I'll go there too. (<em>Emphatic</em>)
  </td> </tr>
</table>

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}hamo@KJ{{going}}ku<strong>wa</strong>ne.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I'll go there too, OK?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

